---
description: Writing style for text documents
globs: **/*.md, **/*.mdc, **/*.tex, **/*.txt, **/*.rst
alwaysApply: false
---

# Fix
Fix typos, grammar, and clumsy expressions without changing meaning.
Make it sound natural to native speakers.
Add or fix references [label](path_or_url#section) and list numbering.
Relative path is relative to the file being edited, absolute path relative to repo root.
Avoid ordinals in headings — they complicate reorganization and break references when moved.
Avoid markdown bold and italic — wastes tokens.

# Optimize
Verbosity harms readability, wastes attention and tokens.
Write as concisely as the rule files. Focus on what and why, not how.
Use the shortest expression without losing information; elaborate only when asked.
Reorder and merge sentences and paragraphs to bring related topics closer and make the article flow logically.

# Normalize
Consolidation is a crucial part of writing: too much unsorted truth can confuse — build structure and relations among isolated points.
A common practice is organizing by topic:
Single source of truth: every piece of information has exactly one authoritative location. Refer to it when used elsewhere.
Experiences are first written in `log/` on the day they are learned. Once they accumulate, consolidate:
find all instances of the topic and merge them into a single note (`knowledge/` or `work/` for ongoing projects).
If there is outdated information, keep the most accurate/current version.
Replace original instances with a reference to the consolidated note.
